{"author":"Iso Tester","data":{"body":"PASS 1 plan review — T11 (Data-migration / backfill safety) [overlay]\n\nThis overlay applies only weakly. `compiled_state` is a derived projection re-built by the reducer from an append-only, file-per-ticket event log (`reduce_ticket`); SNAPSHOTs fold prior events and `process_snapshot` simply copies keys back into state (src/rebar/reducer/_processors.py:515-519). Adding `managed_refs` involves NO blocking DDL, NO large-table lock, NO giant transaction, and NO standalone backfill job — the field materializes per-ticket on the next reduce/compaction. So T11(a) online/expand-contract, (b) batching, and (e) blocking-lock-rollback concerns are largely not-applicable by construction (PASS).\n\nAFFIRMATIONS:\n- T11(a)/(b): No single blocking DDL on a large table and no one-giant-transaction backfill — the persisted format is a re-derived projection over per-ticket event files, so the new field appears incrementally without a migration job.\n- T11(e): The append-only event log makes the change additive and non-destructive; a back-out (stop folding the field) cannot lose source events, so there is no data-loss-on-partial-failure risk.\n\nFINDING (one transitional/backfill gap the plan under-specifies):\n\n- [ ] Specify the behavior of `should_propagate_removal` for tickets whose LATEST SNAPSHOT predates `managed_refs` (the key is absent/empty until that ticket is next compacted). An empty `managed_refs` makes the gate ADOPT every inbound peer ref — so a legitimate LOCAL removal on a not-yet-recompacted ticket would be resurrected during the transitional window, which is exactly the churn this story exists to kill. The AC covers durability for a compaction performed under the NEW code, but not the EXISTING corpus of pre-change SNAPSHOTs. Add an AC for the absent/empty-`managed_refs` case and how it converges (e.g. re-derive the union from post-snapshot LINK/parent-EDIT events even when the SNAPSHOT lacks the key, or run/document a recompaction sweep).\n  criteria: T11\n  location: Acceptance Criteria — the `managed_refs` / compact_ticket bullets\n  evidence: AC says \"a removal performed before OR after a compaction boundary still propagates,\" but that test compacts under the new code; the plan does not state what happens for a ticket last compacted under OLD code, where `process_snapshot` restoring no `managed_refs` key is a silent no-op (src/rebar/reducer/_processors.py:515-519). This is the migration \"pre-existing rows / dual-write window\" dimension (T11-d) for a re-derived projection. The label precedent `local_label_intent` reads SNAPSHOT `compiled_state.tags` (src/rebar/_engine/rebar_reconciler/local_label_intent.py:63), so an absent-key fallback strategy is the relevant unknown here.\n  suggested_fix: (empty — the convergence strategy, lazy re-derive vs. recompaction sweep, is a design choice for the author; either, once chosen and stated, satisfies the criterion.)"},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"COMMENT","timestamp":1782535848112813001,"uuid":"7097964d-b726-469c-91fc-513043dcc6f8"}